5|$|In the United States and Canada, {{the drink}} is popular in instant form, made {{with hot water}} or milk from a packet {{containing}} mostly cocoa powder, sugar, and dry milk. This is the thinner of the two main variations. It is very sweet and may be topped with marshmallows, whipped cream, {{or a piece of}} solid <b>chocolate.</b> Hot <b>chocolate</b> was first brought to North America as early as the 17th century by the Dutch, but the first time colonists began selling hot <b>chocolate</b> was around 1755. Traditionally, hot <b>chocolate</b> has been associated with cold weather, winter, and dessert in the United States and Canada.|$|E
